            I had of late yeares an old man to my tenant, who customablye
a great tyme, went twise in the wéeke to London, eyther with fruit
or with pescodes, when time serued therefore. And as hee was comming
homewarde on blacke heathe, at the ende thereof next to shooters
hill, he ouertoke two Rufflars, the one manerly waiting on ye
other, as one had ben the maister, and the other the man or seruant

carying his maister cloke: This olde man was very gladde that hée
might haue their cōpany ouer the bill, bicause that day he had made
a good market, for he had seuen shillings in his purse, and an olde
angell, which this pore man had thought had not bene in his purse,
for he willed his wife ouer night to take out the same Angell, and
lay it vp vntill his comming home againe. And he verely thought
